def: Having tubular nostrils, as the petrels.
A class of flowerless plants, embracing ferns, horsetails, clubmosses, quillworts, and other like plants. See the Note underCryptogamia.-- Pter"i*do*phyte`, n.

A contrivance for regulating and controlling motion, as: (a)The lever or index in a watch, which controls the effective length ofthe hairspring, and thus regulates the vibrations of the balance. (b)The governor of a steam engine. (c) A valve for controlling theadmission of steam to the steam chest, in a locomotive.
A message sent by a submarine telegraphic cable.
A sulphide having two atoms of sulphur in the molecule; adisulphide, as in iron pyrites, FeS2; -- less frequently calledbisulphuret.
Gay; merry; sprightly; joyous; glad; cheerful; as, a blithespirit.The blithe sounds of festal music. Prescott.A daughter fair, So buxom, blithe, and debonair. Milton.
One of the air cells of algals.
Of or pertaining to the machinery of a poem; acting or used asa machine.[Obs.] Dryden.
Marked with botches; full of botches; poorly done. "This botchybusiness." Bp. Watson.
Of or pertaining to aërolites; meteoric; as, aërolitic iron.Booth.
